What is academic writing, why is it important and so difficult? How much work should I put into the writeup? **A lot**.

::: {.infobox2 .information data-latex="warning"}
When you have your first full version of the report, then you probably got about 50% of the work done! -- *Andrea Ichino*
:::

## First Impression

::: {.infobox2 .information data-latex="warning"}
There is no second chance for a first impression.
:::

Often the first think people see about your work is the **title**, **introduction** and perhaps a *killer graph*. 

- First goal: **Impress** (as a person + with your work)
- Second goal: **Define your contribution** (this might be subtle) 
- Third goal: Make your work known (publish)

::: {.infobox2 .information data-latex="warning"}
If you are uncertain about anything, people think you are also uncertain about your work.
:::

### The Title

Think about it: This is how people will remember your work – or not. 

Make it interesting! Give Keywords. What are the strength of your work (new data, new methods, new question)? 

<!-- Example: „ICT and education: Evidence from Student Home Addresses“ -->
<!-- No mention of „England“ -->
<!-- „ICT“ very general, paper is „only“ about broadband availability (you get told in abstract) -->
<!-- „Student Home Addresses“ –detailed (admin) data!  -->

All words in the title are to be capitalized except definite and indefinite articles, prepositions of all kind and coordinating conjunctions. 

<details>
<summary>
**Examples**
</summary>
<!-- *German Foreign Direct Investment in Poland: An Investigation into the Regionalisation Pattern and the Role of Special Economic Zones.* -->

> The Colonial Origins of Comparative Development:
An Empirical Investigation
>
> `r tufte::quote_footer('Acemoglu, D., Johnson, S., & Robinson, J. A. (2001). The colonial origins of comparative development: An empirical investigation. American economic review, 91(5), 1369-1401.')`

> The Relationship Between Relative Income & Happiness: An Empirical Analysis Utilising GSOEP Panel Data And Fixed-Effects Models
>
> `r tufte::quote_footer('Ismail Ridaa (BA Thesis)')`

> Take the Long Way Home: Flexible Work Arrangements
and the Commuting Life Satisfaction Nexus
>
> `r tufte::quote_footer('Marco Kühne')`
</details>

### The Introduction
<!-- Referees decide on your paper after reading the intro –if not long before! -->

Put everything in there!

You find a lot of useful hints on the web:

- <https://www.scribbr.com/academic-essay/introduction/> 
- <https://writingcenter.uagc.edu/introductions-conclusions>
- <https://blog.hubspot.com/marketing/write-stronger-introductions>

But I would like to shift your focus to this particular one:

<https://clauswilke.com/dataviz/telling-a-story.html> 

Most data visualization (or analysis) is done for the purpose of communication. We have an insight about a dataset, and we have a potential audience, and we would like to convey our insight to our audience. [...]

To communicate our insight successfully, we will have to present the audience with a clear and exciting story. [...]

Your goal in telling a story should be to use facts and logical reasoning to get your audience interested and excited. [...]

To tell a complete story, we will usually need multiple visualizations. For example, when giving a presentation, we may first show some background or motivational material, then a figure that creates a challenge, and eventually some other figure that provides the resolution.

It is, however, also possible to condense an entire story arc into a single figure. Such a figure must contain a challenge and a resolution at the same time, and it is comparable to a story arc that starts with a lead.

**Examples of Killer Graphs**

