## R Markdown 

### Block quotes

Source: <https://bookdown.org/yihui/rmarkdown/tufte-quotes.html>



> „Use block quotes parsimoniously. “
>
> `r tufte::quote_footer(' Marco Kühne')`

### BibTeX

Source: <https://bookdown.org/yihui/rmarkdown-cookbook/bibliography.html>

- Create an empty text document in the directory of your markdown document, name it `references`. 
- It will probably  automatically be created as `references.txt`. You can change the file type by simply renaming the file extension into `references.bib`. [Here is how you do this on Windows](https://helpdesk.flexradio.com/hc/en-us/articles/204676189-How-to-change-a-File-Extension-in-Windows)
- In this text/bib file you can store a resource as this:

```{r , echo=FALSE, out.width="50%", fig.cap="A BibTeX Entry in a Text File.", fig.align='center'}
knitr::include_graphics("bibtex-entry.png")
```

Items can be cited directly within the documentation using the syntax `@key` where key is the citation key in the first line of the entry, e.g., `@R-base` which turns into @R-base. To put citations in parentheses, use `[@key]`. To cite multiple entries, separate the keys by semicolons, e.g., `[@key-1; @key-2; @key-3]`. To suppress the mention of the author, add a minus sign before @, e.g., `[-@R-base]`.

Why do we get the information from? Use Google Scholar 

<https://scholar.google.de/scholar?hl=de&q=Stutzer%20and%20Frey%20(2008)&lr=>

```{r , echo=FALSE, out.width="80%", fig.cap="Google Scholar Search.", fig.align='center'}
knitr::include_graphics("gs.png")
```

<!-- @article{stutzer2008stress, -->
<!--   title={Stress that doesn't pay: The commuting paradox}, -->
<!--   author={Stutzer, Alois and Frey, Bruno S}, -->
<!--   journal={Scandinavian Journal of Economics}, -->
<!--   volume={110}, -->
<!--   number={2}, -->
<!--   pages={339--366}, -->
<!--   year={2008}, -->
<!--   publisher={Wiley Online Library} -->
<!-- } -->

**Attention**: Google Scholar is very reliable but not perfect. At the end, you need to invest time to check all your bibtex resources and fix potential problems. 

